<h2><center>MRC CyberAlerts Conservative Journalists</center></h2>
<P></B><BR>
<P>In response to the growing demand for MRC research, we are using 
state-of-the-art technology to reach conservative leaders instantaneously. Several 
          times a week MRC Executive Director Brent Baker sends &quot;CyberAlert&quot; 
messages via electronic mail to a network of talk radio hosts and key 
conservative leaders in the media. 
<P>Each conservative journalist receives the latest intelligence on the leftist 
media. CyberAlerts' subjects have included the findings from the recent 
Roper Center poll for the Freedom Forum, which showed that 89 percent of 
Washington journalists voted for Clinton, and that only 2 percent considered 
themselves conservative. 
<P>The CyberAlert membership list has grown to include heavy hitters like 
talk show hosts <B>G. Gordon Liddy</B> (nationally syndicated), 
<B>Neal Boortz</B> (WSB, Atlanta), <B>David 
Brudnoy</B> (WBZ, Boston), <B>Mark Davis</B> (WBAP, Fort Worth), 
<B>Jim Eason</B> (KGO, San Francisco), <B>David 
Gold</B> (KLIF, Dallas), <B>Jason Lewis</B> (KSTP, St. 
 Paul), <B>Jan Mickelson</B> (WHO, Des Moines), 
<B>Wes Minter</B> (KCMO, Kansas City), <B>Mike 
Rosen</B> (KOA, Denver), and <B>Barry Young</B> (KFYI, Phoenix). Newspaper 
columnists like <B>Evan Gahr</B> from the <I>New York 
Post</I>, <B>Dick Williams </B>from the <I>Atlanta 
Journal</I>, <B>Don Feder</B> from the <I>Boston 
Herald</I>; and nationally syndicated columnists 
<B>Cal Thomas</B> and <B>Arianna Huffington</B> also use these alerts in 
their stories. Others receiving CyberAlerts include 
<I>The American Spectator</I>'s Editor-in-Chief  
<B>R. Emmett Tyrrell Jr.</B>, and Executive Editor 
<B>Wladyslaw Pleszczynski</B>; <B>Tony Snow</B> from 
<I>Fox News Sunday</I>; and <B>Fred Barnes</B>, the Executive 
Editor of <I>The</I> <I>Weekly Standard</I>.
<P>Overnight these CyberAlerts have become an essential tool for 
conservatives in the media fighting the blatant liberal bias that pervades the mainstream 
media. <br>
<p>
<br>
<b><i><center>And here's some feedback we've received from our CyberAlerts:</center></i></b>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<P>Today's &quot;Media Reality Check&quot; is unbelievably 
<U>great</U> (did it on my radio show). 
You're doing great work.
You were great on Rush , too.
<blockquote>-- A personal note from Mary Matalin, CBS radio talk    
 show host.</blockquote>
<p>
 "As always you are doing a simply superb and bang-up job! I use your material on my show almost every day. Needless to say, your daily updates are 
excellent...&quot; <blockquote>-- Barry Young at KFYI in Phoenix.</blockquote>
<p>
&quot;Thanks...these things are great.&quot; <blockquote>-- Doug Kellett at 
WRCG in Columbus, Georgia.</blockquote>
<P>&quot;You're sending great stuff. Could you add 
<I>World</I>'s Managing Editor Nick Eicher to your distribution list?&quot;  
 <blockquote>-- Marvin Olasky, Editor of <I>World</I> magazine.</blockquote>
<P>
&quot;Vice President Dan Quayle was very intrigued about the 
press' coverage of the Israeli election. He may 
write his weekly column on this subject next week. Do you have 
any more information?&quot; <blockquote>-- Brad Newby from the office of Dan Quayle.</blockquote>
<P>
&quot;Thanks always, for the terrific job and resource you're providing.&quot; 
<blockquote>-- Wes Minter at KCMO, in Kansas City.</blockquote>   
<P>&quot;You're doing a fabulous job! Keep up the 
pressure.&quot; <blockquote>-- Cal Thomas, syndicated columnist.</blockquote>
<P>&quot;I think this fax and E-mail system will spread your 
message more quickly and effectively. Speaking of that, could you add 
my TV colleague, Bill Shipp to your list? [He] now lives in 
Newt's district, puts out a newsletter, and sends his very 
conservative column to 43 newspapers in Georgia.&quot; 
 <blockquote>-- Dick Williams.</blockquote>

<p><br><br>
<h2><B><center>MRC Editor on Entitlement Reform</center></B></h2>
<P>Did you know that if Social Security and Medicare are not reformed, future generations may face tax rates as high as 84 
percent? Or that more young people believe in UFOs than believe they 
will ever get any money from Social Security? You may not have known 
of these unpleasant facts because no one in the media reports them.
<P>But entitlement reform is becoming an increasingly important issue 
in conservative circles, and the MRC is part of the dialogue. Recently 
Tim Lamer, director of the MRC's Free Market Project, participated in a 
panel discussion hosted by the Heritage Foundation's Third Generation 
Program, a series of lectures for young conservatives. Representatives from the Cato Institute and the 
Heritage Foundation also served on the panel while many young conservatives 
from various think tanks and Capitol Hill attended 
the discussion.
<P>All four panelists reflected on why, with the 
impending retirement of the Baby Boom generation, 
entitlement reform is the most important econ-omic 
issue facing young people. Lamer addressed why reforming these programs should be a major concern for all wings of 
the conservative movement and how the movement can bring media 
attention to bear on the issue.<BR>
<br>
<br>
<p>
<h2><B><center>Broader Project Replaces FEMI</center></b></h2>

In order to reflect its new, broad-
      ened focus, the MRC's Free 
      Enterprise &amp; Media Institute (FEMI) has changed its name to 
the <B>Free Market Project</B>.
<P>Beginning this year, the Free Market Project is undertaking 
joint projects with other conservative public policy or business organizations 
to help them educate reporters about their particular concerns. 
Currently, the Free Market Project is engaged in a joint project with Consumer Alert, 
the free-market consumer group, to study how popular consumer 
publications cover business and free enterprise. These projects give the 
conservative movement and the business community the scientific research they need 
to educate the media regarding their biases, and to confront them directly 
if necessary.
<P>In addition to the new joint projects, the Free Market Project 
will continue to publish the newsletter 
<I>MediaNomics</I> on a monthly basis, and FEMI's Quarterly Breakfast Forums, 
designed to educate the media about free enterprise issues, will continue 
to be held every few months.
</B>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><i><center><a href="flas1-6.html">"Flash"</a></center></i></b>


