<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Word of the Day - "Wrong" page</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<img src="/nationalreview/images/word.gif" ALT="William F. Buckley, Jr.'s Word of the Day">
<P>
<HR WIDTH=50%>

<H2> WRONG</H2>
<hr>
<A HREF="word.html">Try again, Back to Word of the Day</A>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
</CENTER>
</body>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT15-B17-59</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA035-000696-B008-99</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.empower.org:80/nationalreview/27jan97/week.html 204.71.237.79 19970209232821 text/html 15144
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 23:29:06 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 01:46:02 GMT
Content-length: 14960
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#fffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<title>The Week -- January 27, 1997</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/week.gif" ALT="The Week">
</center>
<P>
<center>January 27, 1997</center>
<p>
<HR>
<P>
<!--------------------------------------------------------------------->



<LI>Vice President Gore very decently offered to fly all the way from New Hampshire to attend Bill Clinton's Inaugural.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>``If the [Republicans] don't come around, we'll use children's health the way we used Medicare, and that's a promise and a commitment,'' AFL-CIO president John Sweeney told the American Public health Association recently. We have been warned: an alleged upsurge in the number of children without health insurance will figure prominently in the liberal establishment's Winter-Spring Offensive. But Merrill Matthews, writing for the Dallas-based National Center for Policy Analysis, points out that a) the ``upsurge'' is still quite small; b) costly mandated benefits, like compulsory maternity leave, are forcing employers to cancel health-insurance policies, exposing children; and c), uninsured children are disproportionately immigrants and the children of immigrants -- overall, 40.6 per cent of foreign-born non-citizens were uninsured in 1995, versus only 13.6 per cent of the native-born. ``Any nationwide program for children threatens to evolve into an entitlement program primarily benefitting legal and illegal immigrants,'' writes Matthews. he and the NCPA are to be congratulated for exposing liberal-establishment hokum -- and for ignoring conservative-establishment blindness about the immigrant dimension of  many American policy problems.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>The Clinton Administration wants legalized pot out of California and Arizona and in the White House where it belongs.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Soon enough it will be gut-check time again for congressional Republicans on race preferences. Rep. Charles Canady (R., Fla.) is set to re-introduce his bill banning racial discrimination in federal hiring, promotions, and contracts early in the 105th Congress. Judiciary Committee Chairman henry Hyde is willing to give the legislation an airing in his committee, which would probably pass it in one form or another. The outstanding question is whether the House leadership will get behind the bill and allow a vote on the House floor. memories of last year, when leadership not only sat on the Canady bill but countenanced the reauthorization of federal programs shot through with quotas and set-asides, are not encouraging. Since then, of course, California voters dramatically demonstrated their opposition to state-sponsored discrimination. When will Newt Gingrich and Dick Armey?

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Moderate Republicans, as everyone knows, are trying hard to pull their party back to mainstream America. So what's their top priority this year? According to John McCaslin in the Washington Times, the congressmen in the ``Tuesday Lunch Brunch'' want to restore funds to the National Endowment for the Arts. Memo to the members: if crucifixes in urine represented mainstream America, there wouldn't have been a GOP majority in the first place.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Having had an attack of common sense when ``Ebonics'' first hit the news, the usual suspects are now engaged in revisionism. The Oakland school board wasn't really going to teach Ebonics; it wasn't really suggesting that Ebonics had a basis in black genes; it wasn't really trolling for federal cash from bilingual programs. Instead, the board was looking for a ``bridge'' between Ebonics and standard English, as teachers under the new dispensation would teach the latter, but not ridicule the former. Never mind that any fair reading of the board's original resolution makes it clear that it was doing exactly what it was accused of doing. And never mind the fact that bilingual education, as currently practiced, means teaching ``native'' languages, and not English. Ecen the mild, revisionist proposal makes no sense. In other periods of American history, waves of immigrants have learned English without teachers who were ``sensitive'' to their first language. The kids will get over being told they be doing something wrong. They won't get over being told they're doing something right when they aren't.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>On Meet the Press, Anthony Lake, the Administration's nominee for Director of Central Intelligence, was asked whether he believed Alger Hiss was a spy. His answer: ``I've read a couple of books that certainly offered a lot of evidence that he may have been. I don't think it's conclusive.'' Report from the late CIA: ``The U.S.S. Maine -- Sunk, or Afloat? You be the judge.''

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Texas GOP Chairman Tom Pauken is running better than expected in his bid to succeed Haley Barbour as chairman of the Republican National Committee. Pauken pledges to uproot the Washington-based consultants responsible for the party's ``poll-driven policy'' and to tend the grassroots. At a Washington press briefing, he appeared ready for the national spotlight, polished, sure-footed, and articulate. Neither of the leading candidates, ex-Gov. Steve Merrill of New Hampshire and RNC General Counsel David Norcross of New Jersey, has enough votes at present to win election at the January 17 meeting. Committee members fear that a Merrill chairmanship would be a full-employment program for the Dole campaign and that Norcross would represent Christine Todd Whitman's Northeast wing of the GOP. Pauken's prospects are hurt by the opposition of Barbour himself and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, but if he can put together a coalition with conservative competitors like Jim Nicholson of Colorado and Chuck Yob of Michigan, he has a shot -- and deserves to win.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>Sen. Christopher Dodd, eight days before the elections, expressed his weariness with the campaign and said that in a week plus one day he could tell the truth ``again.'' We're following this story closely and will let you know when he does.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>What could be more American? According to a report in the Los Angeles Times, at least 19 non-citizens voted in November's race between Rep. Bob Dornan (R., Calif.) and Loretta Sanchez, which Miss Sanchez won by less than 1,000 votes. The illegal voters were registered by the group Hermandad Mexicana Nacional (National Mexican Brotherhood), which registered roughly 1,300 people this year, nearly 600 of whom voted in the Dornan - Sanchez race. The Times found its 19 illegal voters out of a random sample of a mere 64 registered voters. How many more were there? No one knows. Small wonder a non-citizen feels comfortable voting in American elections: they are fast becoming as secure and reliable as those back home.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Mrs. Shucheng Huang, 55, had to look up the word ``strike'' when the United Auto Workers local called one at Abex Friction Products in April. But since then she has learned quite a bit about the real meaning of ``organized labor.'' When she continued to work, one of her car windows was broken. Two weeks later, a severed cow's head was left on her hood. A slingshot was used to smash her windshield while she was parking. Other workers had their tires slashed and windows broken, or awoke to find cattle heads in their yards. Someone shot at a window of Thomas Jones's house, and a message on the men's room wall at the plant said, ``Tom Jones, you're going to be dead before it's over with'' (quote courtesy of Tim Sullivan, Northern Virginia Daily). The National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation has filed suit on behalf of ten workers who were targeted by the UAW's terror campaign. Such coercion is commonplace. What's especially scandalous is that under federal law, as interpreted by the Supreme Court, union violence is legal if directed toward ``legitimate union objectives'' (U.S. v. Emmons, 1973). Abuses are inevitable under a regime of forced unionism. But if Congress is not yet ready to pass a National Right to Work Act, it should at least hold hearings on union thuggery and pass a Freedom from Violence Act removing union officials' status as a class above the law.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>We have been asked to explain how Mr. Newt's problems differ from the Administration's. Easy. Mr. Newt is accused of an ethics violation, whereas Mr. Clinton's wife, friends, associates, fundraisers, business partners, Cabinet members, lawyers, White House staffers, political operatives, cronies, and ``Arkansas mafia'' are seldom accused of anything worse than felonies. Next.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Chinese Premier Li Peng paid a holiday visit to Moscow December 26 - 28, meeting with Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin and setting the stage for an April summit in Moscow between Yeltsin and Chinese President Jiang Zemin. Ever since Yeltsin's triumphal visit to Peking last spring, the relationship has blossomed into what both sides call a ``strategic partnership.'' The Chinese endorse Russian stands on Chechnya and NATO enlargement; the Russians return the favor by endorsing Chinese positions on human rights, Taiwan, and Hong Kong. The Russians are selling SU-27 jet fighters and related production technology to China. Both sides condemn the notion that any superpower should dictate to other countries. (In case you wondered, that means us.) Meanwhile, the Clinton Administration proceeds on the assumption that Russia and China are our friends.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>Slobodan Milosevic has tried hard to shut down B-92, Serbia's only non-government-controlled radio station. Newly independent media in Poland and the Czech Republic struggle for survival. Throughout Central and Eastern Europe, those working to plant democracy look to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty to keep broadcasting the unfiltered truth -- as a check on unreconstructed Communists, as a standard for fledgling free media to emulate, and as a symbol of the West's support for their democratic future. Yet RFE/RL is embattled in Congress: budget cuts have eliminated its Hungarian service and threaten to curtail its Czech and Polish services. Serbo-Croatian broadcasting urgently needs to be expanded, but the money isn't there. All federal funding for RFE/RL is due to end in December 1999. This makes no  sense. Eastern Europeans -- and we -- need RFE/RL.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>What do Shakespeare, Mozart, and Leonardo have in common? Each is a towering figure in European culture and each has been rejected as too controversial to appear on the new Euro currency. The Bard slammed Jews, Mozart puffed the Masons, Leonardo might have been homosexual. Despairing of famous Europeans, the European Monetary Institute has decreed that the new currency will feature architecture -- gateways, windows, bridges. Or, as one Euro-skeptic put it, ``It will remind people that a single currency is a gateway to mass unemployment, a window to misery, and a bridge to civil unrest.''

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Administration officials are refusing to appear on Fox News Sunday with Tony Snow, in the hopes of strangling the show in the crib. Any thoughts on this political attempt to squelch journalism? Meg? Pinch? Dan?

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Sterling Burnett of the National Center for Policy Analysis in Dallas has dug up a nice 1990 quote from Timothy Wirth, the Under Secretary of State for Global Affairs, who is generally credited with giving U.S. foreign policy an increasingly Green hue: ``We've got to ride the global-warming issue. Even if the theory of global warming is wrong, we will be doing the right thing in terms of economic policy and environmental policy.'' It is interesting to know that the Administration's top Green doesn't really care whether the theory of global warming is correct. It's a good scare, and that's enough.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>The press will get off Newt's back once he uses the words ``bureaucratic snafu.''
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>Maryland (which never seceded from the Union) allowed the Sons of Confederate Veterans to buy specialty license plates showing the Stars and Bars -- until black and liberal politicians objected. South Carolina properly removed the Confederate battle flag from its Capitol dome, where it implicitly claimed the respect of all South Carolinians, and where it recalled the state's open support of slavery 136 years ago. But a specialty license plate allows individuals to honor the memory of other individuals, whose actions were often gallant, and whose motives were mixed. Robert E. Lee had freed his slaves. Some Confederate soldiers were ex-slaves. It is peculiarly modern to despise losers. The ultimate losers are ourselves.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>An editing error in our recent editorial ``The Deep Green Sea'' [Dec. 23] may have misled readers to assume that fertilizing the southern oceans with iron could reverse, rather than slow, the accumulation of carbon dioxide in the earth's atmosphere. But we remain encouraged by this development. Absent an economic means of putting the atmosphere into reverse, it's a good thing that scientists have located the brake pedal.


<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>It not be whefuh Ebonics be ungrammatical English but how kids be feelin' 'bout it.


<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>Even for liberalism in its late, decadent stage, it's a stretch to make a hero out of a racist, sexist scumbag like Larry Flynt, but the nation's opinion leaders are managing. Director Milos Forman has made a film, The People v. Larry Flynt, that portrays the Hustler publisher as a charming, witty man and a passionate defender of First Amendment freedoms. Forman makes Flynt lament not being able to have more children, though he abandoned five of them, one of whom accuses him of having sexually molested her. The film skips over the racist cartoons and the violent, degrading depictions of sex in the magazine. The only odious characters in the film are nuns, Jerry Falwell, and anyone else offended by Flynt's product. That The People v. Larry Flynt is being hailed as ``timely,'' ``important,'' and even ``patriotic'' art just marks another step in the American elite's slouch toward Gomorrah.


<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>Sentences of the week, from a laudatory story in U.S. News & World Report on assisted suicide in the Netherlands: ``Contrary to law, some three-fifths of all Dutch cases of euthanasia go unreported. . . . 1 in 5 of the unreported cases involved the most vexing kind of euthanasia, death without a patient's consent.'' Vexing indeed. Some would call it dysthanasia. Or homicide.




<P>
<hr>
<P>


<!------------------------------------------------------------------>
<p>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<p>
<a href="/nationalreview/welcome.html">Return to <B><I>NATIONAL REVIEW'S</I></B> homepage</a>
<BR>
</body>

